                <h2>Letter N</h2>
                <p>The 'N' in ASL is represented by placing the thumb underneath the first two fingers (index and middle
                    fingers) while keeping the ring and pinky fingers extended. This sign mimics the shape of the letter
                    'N' with two fingers over the thumb.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, all fingers extended, and
                        palm facing yourself.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Place your thumb under your index and middle fingers,
                        slightly towards the palm.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curling Fingers:</strong> Curl your index and middle fingers down over your thumb,
                        holding it in place.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ring and Pinky Extension:</strong> Keep your ring and pinky fingers extended straight
                        out. They should be the only fingers not touching the thumb.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Ensure the two fingers are securely over the thumb and the ring
                        and pinky fingers are clearly extended to accurately represent the letter 'N'.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practicing the 'N' sign is important for its distinct structure. The letter 'N' is a key component of
                    the ASL alphabet and requires precision for effective communication.</p>
